Welcome to notebook ten of the Java track. Notebook nine put a hypertext transfer protocol front door on our Spring service. This notebook plugs in the inside, the part where the persistent state actually lives. The topic is Spring Data. By the end of this session you will be able to map Java classes to database tables, define repository interfaces that write their own structured query language for you, use derived query methods, write custom queries when derivation cannot reach, page through large result sets, manage transactions correctly, and evolve your database schema safely with migrations.

Here is the map for what we will cover. First, why Spring Data exists and what boilerplate it removes. The Jakarta Persistence Application Programming Interface, j p a for short, in one paragraph, with Hibernate as the default implementation. The data source bean and the essential j p a properties. Mapping a Java class to a table with at sign Entity, at sign Id, at sign Generated Value, at sign Column, and at sign Table. The four relationship annotations, one to many, many to one, many to many, and one to one, plus the owning side concept. Cascading and orphan removal. Fetch types, lazy versus eager, and the famous n plus one query problem. The repository hierarchy, from Repository through Crud Repository up to Jpa Repository. Derived query methods, where Spring inspects the method name and writes the query. The at sign Query annotation for j p q l and native structured query language. The at sign Modifying annotation for write queries. Paging and sorting with Pageable, Page, and Slice. Transactions with at sign Transactional, with notes on propagation, isolation, read only mode, and the self invocation gotcha. Dynamic queries with Specifications and Query by Example as the escape hatches. And finally, database migrations with Flyway, the dominant choice in the Spring world, plus a contrast with Liquibase.

Let us start with why Spring Data exists. A typical data access layer, hand written without any framework help, repeats the same plumbing in every class. Open a connection. Prepare a statement. Bind the parameters. Execute. Iterate the result set. Map each row to a Java object. Close everything in a finally block. Handle structured query language exceptions. Multiply that pattern by every table and every query in your application, and you end up with hundreds of lines of identical, error prone code, which is also where most of your bugs hide.

Spring Data takes that plumbing and reduces it to two things you actually write. An entity, which describes what the data looks like in Java. And a repository interface, which describes what queries you need. Spring generates the rest at startup, using the reflection mechanics from notebook seven.

One paragraph on the j p a stack. J p a, the Jakarta Persistence Application Programming Interface, is the standard specification for object relational mapping on the java virtual machine. It defines the annotations like at sign Entity. It defines the Entity Manager interface for create, read, update, delete operations. And it defines a query language called j p q l, the Java Persistence Query Language, which is an object oriented dialect of structured query language. J p a is just the spec. To actually use it, you need an implementation. Hibernate is the de facto implementation that Spring Boot pulls in by default. Spring Data j p a layers a repository abstraction on top of j p a, so you rarely touch Hibernate directly. The stack from top to bottom is, your code, then Spring Data j p a, then j p a the spec, then Hibernate the implementation, then j d b c, then the database driver, then the database itself.

The data source bean is the connection pool. Spring Boot auto configures one, using HikariCP by default, from the standard properties under spring dot datasource. The url, username, and password are the three main properties. J p a itself reads properties under spring dot j p a.

One property worth a moment of attention. Spring dot j p a dot hibernate dot d d l dash auto controls what Hibernate does to your database schema at startup. The four options are none, validate, update, and create, with a fifth, create dash drop, for ephemeral environments. The right setting for any non trivial project is validate. Validate checks that the database schema matches your entity declarations, and refuses to start if they do not. Update auto adds missing columns, which sounds convenient but is dangerous in production. Update does not drop anything, so your schema can drift over time, and update does not handle renames or type changes. Create and create dash drop wipe and rebuild the schema on startup, which is appropriate only for tests. For real schema management, use Flyway or Liquibase, which we will cover later in this notebook.

Now, entities. An entity is a class annotated with at sign Entity. J p a tracks each entity as the in memory representation of a row in some table. Every entity needs an at sign Id field, which marks the primary key. J p a also needs a no argument constructor on every entity, which is why we use classes, not records, for entities.

The at sign Table annotation lets you override the table name and declare indexes and unique constraints. The at sign Column annotation lets you override the column name, set nullability, set the maximum length, and mark a column as not updatable. The at sign Generated Value annotation, together with a strategy, controls how the primary key value is assigned. The two most common strategies are IDENTITY, which lets the database generate the value, like the Postgres big serial type, and SEQUENCE, which uses an explicit database sequence.

A small but important detail about enums. By default, j p a stores enum values as their ordinal, that is, the integer position in the declaration. This is fragile. The moment you reorder the enum, every stored ordinal points at the wrong value. Always annotate enum fields with at sign Enumerated of EnumType dot STRING, which stores the enum as its name. The cost is a few extra bytes per row. The benefit is that you cannot accidentally corrupt your data by editing the enum.

One restriction. Records and entities do not mix. J p a needs to mutate fields after construction. To support lazy loading, j p a generates proxies and writes into fields after the constructor runs. To support dirty tracking, j p a watches fields for changes. Records explicitly disallow both. Use a plain class for entities, and reserve records for data transfer objects in the controller layer.

Now, relationships. J p a models the four cardinalities of database relationships with four annotations. The crucial concept is the owning side, which is the side that holds the foreign key in the database.

At sign Many To One is the owning side. The entity declares a field of the target type, marks it with at sign Many To One, and uses at sign Join Column to specify the foreign key column name. Many post rows can point at one user row, so the post entity is the many side, and it holds the foreign key author underscore id.

At sign One To Many is the inverse side. The entity declares a collection field, marks it with at sign One To Many, and crucially uses the mapped By attribute to name the field on the owning side that holds the foreign key. So the user entity has a posts collection mapped by the author field on the post entity. Spring will not create a new join table or foreign key for this side, because the relationship is already represented by the owning side's foreign key.

At sign Many To Many needs a join table, because neither side can hold a single foreign key. You declare the join table name and the two join column sets with the at sign Join Table annotation.

At sign One To One can be modelled either with a shared primary key or with a unique foreign key. It is the least common shape in practice.

The cascade attribute controls what happens to the related entity when you save, update, or delete the owner. Cascade Type dot ALL cascades every operation. Cascade Type dot PERSIST cascades only save operations. Cascade Type dot MERGE cascades only update operations. The orphan Removal attribute set to true deletes child rows when they are removed from the parent's collection.

A piece of repeated advice. Prefer the many to one side as the owner for collections. Keep cascades narrow. Cascade all the things is the source of many why did deleting a user wipe my entire database incidents. Be deliberate.

Every relationship has a fetch type, which controls when the related data is loaded. Fetch Type dot LAZY loads the related entity on first access. Fetch Type dot EAGER loads it immediately, as part of the parent query. The default for at sign One To Many and at sign Many To Many is LAZY. The default for at sign Many To One and at sign One To One is EAGER.

That default for at sign Many To One being EAGER is the source of the most famous j p a performance trap. The n plus one query problem.

Imagine you call find All on a post repository. That issues one query, the find all posts query, returning n rows. Then you iterate the n posts. Each time you access post dot author, j p a triggers another query, namely select from users where id equals the author id of that post. That is n more queries, one per post. The total is n plus one queries to load n posts and their authors. With one post you do not notice. With ten thousand posts your service falls over.

The fix is straightforward. Tell Hibernate to fetch the relationship in the original query. In j p q l, you use a JOIN FETCH clause, which produces a single query with a join. As an alternative, you can use the at sign Entity Graph annotation on the repository method, which declares which attributes to eagerly load for that method. For everything you can control, set fetch type to LAZY everywhere, even on at sign Many To One. Then explicitly join when you actually need the relationship. This makes the cost visible in the query, not hidden inside an innocent looking field access.

Now, the repository hierarchy. Spring Data exposes a stack of empty marker interfaces. You extend the one that gives you the methods you want. From the root down. Repository of t comma id is the base marker, with no methods. Crud Repository adds the basic save, find by id, find all, delete by id, and count. Paging And Sorting Repository adds find all with a Pageable and find all with a Sort. Jpa Repository, at the top of the stack, adds j p a specific methods like flush, delete in batch, and get Reference By Id.

The convention for a Spring Data j p a repository is to extend Jpa Repository of entity and id type. Spring's repository factory generates an implementation at startup. It parses your method names. It inspects your at sign Query annotations. It emits the structured query language for your database dialect. The repository interface is what you write. The implementation is what Spring provides.

The headline feature of Spring Data is derived query methods. You declare a method on the repository interface following a naming convention. Spring parses the name into a query at startup. No body. No structured query language. No annotation.

The parser understands a vocabulary of keywords. The verbs are findBy, countBy, existsBy, and deleteBy. The combinators are And and Or. The comparisons are Between, Less Than, Greater Than, Like, Containing, Starting With, Ending With, In, Not In, Is Null, and Is Not Null. The modifiers are Ignore Case for case insensitive matching, Order By for sorting, and Top or First followed by a number for limiting.

Once you internalise the vocabulary, you get hundreds of queries for free. The trade off is that long, multi clause derived names get hard to read. When a name would have four or more clauses, switch to at sign Query instead.

For anything more complex than the derived vocabulary covers, write an explicit query with at sign Query. Spring Data supports both j p q l and native structured query language.

J p q l operates on the entity model, not the table model. You traverse fields and relationships using dot notation. Post dot author dot email, not posts dot author underscore id. J p a translates the j p q l into the right structured query language for your database dialect. The :name syntax with at sign Param binds named parameters.

You can also return projections from a j p q l query. A projection is a smaller data shape that you do not need the full entity for. Use the SELECT new keyword with a fully qualified constructor call. Spring instantiates a new record or class from the selected columns. This is much faster than loading the full entity when you only need a few fields.

For database specific features that j p q l cannot express, like full text search or window functions, use native structured query language. Set the native Query attribute on at sign Query to true.

Any query that is not a SELECT, that is, any UPDATE or DELETE, needs the at sign Modifying annotation, in addition to at sign Query. At sign Modifying tells j p a to clear the persistence context after the query, so subsequent reads see fresh data. Write queries must also run inside a transaction.

Paging and sorting work uniformly. Pass a Pageable to any query method, derived or annotated, and Spring appends LIMIT and OFFSET clauses, plus a COUNT query for the total. The return type Page of t includes the page contents plus metadata. The total number of elements. The total number of pages. Whether there is a next page. The static factory Page Request dot of takes a page number, a page size, and an optional Sort.

For very large result sets, use Slice of t instead of Page of t. Slice skips the expensive COUNT star query. You lose get Total Elements and get Total Pages. You gain a real performance win for paginating through huge tables.

A useful integration with Spring Web. You can accept a Pageable directly in a rest controller method signature. Spring binds the page, size, and sort query parameters automatically. So a request like question mark page equals zero ampersand size equals twenty ampersand sort equals published At comma desc becomes a properly populated Pageable, with no manual parsing.

Now, transactions. A transaction is a unit of database work that either commits as a whole or rolls back as a whole. J p a needs an active transaction for any write, because the changes accumulate in the persistence context and are flushed to the database at commit time. Spring's at sign Transactional annotation declares the boundary.

Three things to know about at sign Transactional. First. By default, at sign Transactional rolls back on Runtime Exception and commits on checked exceptions. You can change this with the rollback For and no Rollback For attributes. Modern Java code leans unchecked, so the default usually does the right thing.

Second. The read Only equals true attribute lets the j p a provider skip dirty checking and lets the database use read only optimisations. Use it on every query method. It is a free win.

Third. At sign Transactional works via Spring's aspect oriented programming mechanism, the same proxy mechanism we covered in notebook eight. The annotation creates a proxy around the bean. The proxy intercepts calls and manages the transaction. This means the same self invocation gotcha applies. One method on a bean calling another at sign Transactional method on the same bean bypasses the proxy and skips the transaction. The second method runs inside whatever transaction the first method already had, if any.

The propagation attribute on at sign Transactional controls what happens when a transactional method is called from inside an existing transaction. The default is REQUIRED, which means join the existing transaction. The other common value is REQUIRES underscore NEW, which means suspend the outer transaction and start a fresh inner one. Use REQUIRES underscore NEW for cases like audit logging that must commit even if the surrounding work rolls back.

For dynamic queries, where the set of filters is decided at runtime, neither derived methods nor at sign Query fit. Two escape hatches. Specifications, where you extend Jpa Specification Executor on the repository, and compose Specification of t predicates with the and and or methods. Specifications are type safe but verbose. Query by Example, where you build a probe entity with the fields you want to filter on, wrap it in an Example, and the framework derives the query. For most cases you outgrow both and reach for QueryDSL or jOOQ, which give you fluent, type safe query builders that produce structured query language directly. Worth knowing they exist. Not in scope for this notebook.

The final topic, and one of the most important in production, is database migrations. Hibernate's d d l auto update is a footgun in production. The right tool for schema management is a migration framework, which is a tool that runs versioned structured query language scripts against your database in order, and tracks which scripts have been applied. Flyway is the dominant choice in the Spring world. Liquibase is its main alternative.

The Flyway convention is simple. Put your migrations in the src slash main slash resources slash d b slash migration folder, on the classpath. Name each file V then a version number, then double underscore, then a description, then dot s q l. So V one underscore underscore create users dot s q l. V two underscore underscore add posts dot s q l. And so on. Add the flyway dash core dependency to your project. Spring Boot auto configures Flyway. On every startup, Flyway reads the migration folder, looks at the flyway schema history table to see which migrations have already been applied, and runs any new ones in version order.

The rules of safe schema evolution are four. Migrations are append only. Never edit a deployed migration. Make migrations backwards compatible. If a column is going away, first stop writing to it, then deploy, then drop it in a later migration. Keep migrations small and focused. One logical change per file. And test migrations on a copy of production data before you deploy.

Liquibase, in contrast, lets you write migrations in extensible markup language, y a m l, or json, with a declarative domain specific language layered on top of structured query language. Liquibase has stronger rollback support and tracks changes more granularly. Flyway is simpler and more common. Liquibase is preferred in environments that need formal change tracking.

That wraps notebook ten. You now have the full stack for a production Spring service. Spring Core from notebook eight wires the components together. Spring Web from notebook nine handles hypertext transfer protocol. Spring Data from this notebook persists state. Add Flyway for migrations and at sign Transactional for atomicity, and you can write real create, read, update, delete services end to end.

Notebook eleven turns to Spring Boot in production. The pieces that make a Spring application deployable. Auto configuration. The at sign Configuration Properties pattern. Actuator endpoints for health and metrics. Structured logging. The integrated test slices, at sign Spring Boot Test, at sign Web Mvc Test, at sign Data Jpa Test. Testcontainers for real database integration tests. Plus messaging with the Spring Kafka project, and a brief tour of the Java Message Service and Spring AMQP for RabbitMQ. Notebook twelve closes the track with Spring Cloud and the distributed system primitives.
